vectorData.altText: That's right!  A padding layer of adipose and the internal vertebral venous plexus (B) are contained within the extradural (epidural space) – space between the bony vertebral canal and the spinal dura.

Between the bony vertebral canal and the dura is the extradural (epidural) space. It contains a padding layer of adipose and the internal vertebral venous plexus.
The dura mater is a thick, tough membrane. Deep to the dura is the more delicate arachnoid mater. Together, the dura and arachnoid form the dural sac, which surrounds the spinal cord loosely. 
The cerebrospinal fluid (CSF)-filled subarachnoid space separates the arachnoid mater from the delicate pia mater. The hydrostatic pressure of the CSF holds the arachnoid against the dura.

Between the bony surface of the vertebral canal and the spinal cord are layers of adipose, membranes and a fluid-filled space.
The meninges are the three layers of membranes that surround and enclose the spinal cord within the vertebral column. From superficial to deep, they are the dura, arachnoid and pia.
